<div class="prose max-w-none">

  <p>The Chinese zodiac (生肖 shēngxiào) is a 12-year cycle where each year is represented by an animal. Unlike Western astrology, which is based on birth month, the Chinese zodiac is determined by your birth year. It influences personality analysis, marriage compatibility, career choices, and even baby planning — Dragon years consistently see birth rate spikes across Chinese communities worldwide. Understanding the zodiac is essential for anyone interested in Chinese culture.</p>

  <h2 id="origin">Origin of the Chinese Zodiac</h2>

  <p>The most famous origin story is the Great Race. The Jade Emperor (玉皇大帝) invited all animals to a race across a river — the first 12 to cross would earn a place in the zodiac.</p>

  <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 2px solid #dc2626; border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; margin: 20px 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0 0 12px; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.1em; color: #dc2626;">🏁 The Great Race (Brief Version)</p>
    <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.8;">The Rat (clever but small) rode on the Ox's back and jumped off at the finish line, arriving first. The Ox came second. The Tiger swam against strong currents for third. The Rabbit hopped across stones and a floating log for fourth. The Dragon flew but stopped to make rain for farmers, arriving fifth. The Snake hid in the Horse's hoof and slithered out suddenly, scaring the Horse — Snake sixth, Horse seventh. The Goat, Monkey, and Rooster worked together on a raft — eighth, ninth, tenth. The Dog played in the water despite being a strong swimmer, coming eleventh. The Pig ate and napped, arriving last at twelfth.</p>
  </div>

